<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Morale Dilema on 04-10-2001 01:19 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Story:
Several months ago I quit EQ, because my business took up too much of my time, and well deciding what to do with my account, an ingame friend approached me and wanted my account , she offered to pay me for it cause she wanted to use em as a ress mule. I didnt like it much but had a need for the sum she offered so agreed. Certain agreements and statements were made though.
1. I could have the account back if I ever returned, if I simply reimbversed the money plus/minus compensation for any new gear/levels.
2. That I could use the account well she had it if I asked her.
3. Although not really an agreement it was under the impression she was gonna use it simply for a ress mule for her/guild.

Well...my business has been doing well, and im at the point where ive hired people to do things I use to do, and have the freetime to play EQ again (im a lvl60 cleric btw).

Well...I came back..my friend was ingame, so I logged in my friends account to talk to her, I told her i'd like to buy my account back, because I was ready to come back.
She got real defensive..and put me on ignore...

So i contacted her guild-leader and asked about me...and found out shes been playing him fulltime now, so I understand why shes attached to him now.

So im sorta stuck in a dilemna.
On the one hand...I really want my character back(yes I know I probly shouldnt have gotten in this situation in the first place but its easy to say that now  ;))
And a deal is a deal...

On the otherhand...shes grown attached to the character, and if I were to take it back by force(i'd still send her the $$ back), that I might earn a bad reputation for "stealing" the account back.

Im a regular here, and just wanted an anon name because im embarassed by the whole thing..but respect the opinions of my friends here..so I ask for any suggestions on a course of action.</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
